@DRCharlesLaw Charles Lawrence began dancing at the age of 9, and had his first dance experiences in the world of show choir, traveling and attending Show Choir Camps of America. Lawrence attended show choir camps every year until 2001. While attending Auburn University in Alabama pursing a degree in secondary education, he became a member of their elite show choir group the Auburn Singers. In 2007, he graduated with his Masters Degree at Southern Illinois University. Lawrence took a short sabbatical from dance to pursue motivational speaking as well as focus on his Doctorate in Forensic Psychology at the Chicago Professional School of Psychology. In 2010, Lawrence made a strong come-back into dance as the choreographer and creative director on a music video for up and coming pop artist JQ. Inspired, Lawrence began working with more rising artists helping to build their careers and stage presence. Lawrence also began teaching master classes throughout the area, as well as becoming the hip hop director at a studio in Chicago’s west suburbs. Simply teaching could not contain Lawrence’s passion for reaching students, so he founded his own company in early 2011, Dance Rogue LLC Intensive Workshops. Since the foundation of Dance Rogue, Lawrence’s company has grown exponentially and attracted a well-accomplished faculty throughout the country. In the fall of 2011, Lawrence took his talents internationally all the way to Baku, Azerbaijan where he was the Assistant Director, Creative Director and Choreographer for the country’s first Hip-Hop Musical, Leyli və Məcnun. Lawrence helped make history while working on the musical, an Azerbaijani story resembling the classic tale of Romeo and Juliet traditionally performed as an opera, by creating the first production of it’s kind on that side of the world using hip hop and other Western influences. Lawrence gained fame quickly while working on the production making television appearances teaching classes, and soon developed a strong following in the Caucasus region other parts of Europe. Lawrence feels blessed to have worked internationally, but feels what is most important as a choreographer is not who he has worked with, but about who he can inspire. In his current endeavors, Lawrence puts his diverse background and knowledge of dance styles into his productions and concept pieces, stylizing and creating character pieces with an almost unlimited variety of influences from urban, ragtime, contemporary, swing, to ballet and jazz. Lawrence’s personal dance style is also a unique blend, incorporating his background in Hip Hop with his own flavor, which he coined as ‘Urban Contemporary.’ Currently, Lawrence’s dream is his reality, with the creative freedom to spend his time traveling and teaching, judging as well as being a stage manager for Starbound plus continuing to work with artists on music videos and stage productions, growing Dance Rogue, and hosting workshops to inspire young dancers throughout the country.

Dance Rogue: Director of Operations

@Trini4Ever Keon K. Nickie is from Arouca, Trinidad and Tobago, and began his dance training in his native country before immigrating to the United States to further his education and dance studies. In 2007, Keon graduated with a BFA from Long Island University in Brooklyn. He has studied with The Ailey School, Balance Dance Theatre, Ballet Hispanico, Cheryl Byron and Something Positive, Deeply Rooted Dance Theater, Eclectic Dance Theatre, and Purelements. He has performed works by choreographers Gary Abbott, Cheryl Byron, Kevin Iega Jeff, Lisa Johnson-Willingham, Kevin A. Joseph, Bill T. Jones, Mark Morris, Troy Powell, Pearl Primus, Nathan Trice, Dr. Melissa Vaughan, Lakai Worrel, and Obediah Wright. Keon was blessed to be a part of the second company of Deeply Rooted Productions before joining the company DanceWorks Chicago in September 2011. Keon became part of the Dance Rogue family in early 2012, and is excited to see where it will take him.

@AdeWillis Chicago Native Ade Willis began his hip-hop training at the age of 12 years old. Willis has trained with top industry choreographers such as, Tucker Barkley, Lyle Beniga, Nick DeMoura, Tony Czar, Tabitha and Napoleon Dumo (NabbyTabs), Laura Edwards, Andye Jamieson, Kevin Maher, and many more.

In 2009 Willis appeared on MTV’s MADE (I want to be a Hip Hop Dancer). Ade recently moved to LA to further his dance career. Within the first week of living in LA, Willis was chosen to appear in Carl Thomas and Snoop Dogg’s music video. He then appeared as a principle dancer in Justin Bieber’s music video “Beauty and a Beat” ft. Nicki Minaj, as well as, is in the CBS Victoria Secret Show (Justin Bieber). Most recently, Ade was the assistant choreographer for Zendaya Coleman’s “Replay” music video.

Moreover, Ade has begun to be recognized for his unique style of choreography. He has been invited to teach all across the world from German and Russia to Australia and Spain. Since 2006 Willis continues to tour the world sharing his knowledge and passion for movement through his teaching abilities. As this is only the beginning of his journey, Ade looks forward to the future!

@BRETTFROSTwire BRETT FROST was born and raised in Orlando, Florida, and began dancing at age 17. In 2010, Brett was selected to be apart of the remake of the legendary dance film “FOOTLOOSE”. Shortly after, Brett moved to Atlanta where he made moves towards continuing a professional career while continuing to train. In 2011 Brett made his move to Los Angeles, California where his fun personality and high energy quickly caught the attention of many. He began teaching at Millennium Dance Complex spreading his energy and knowledge of dance to dancers from around the globe. Since moving Brett has also worked with such artists as Jennifer Lopez, Far East Movement, Mark Ballas (from Dancing with the Stars), & Marcus Houston. Brett was excited to premier as a Dance Rogue 2013 faculty member, and even more so to continue spreading positive energy on the 2014 Summer Tour.

@CourtneyOrtiz Courtney Ortiz, a native of Baltimore, MD is a winner of the NFAA’s YoungArts Scholarship for Modern Dance. Her dance career has allowed her to perform in such places as Canada, Las Vegas, Los Angeles, Atlantic City, Mexico and Australia. Since moving to New York City, Courtney has been a Vegas finalist multiple times on So You Think You Can Dance (top 50 female dancer in S.9), and most recently joined the cast of West Side story as a Jet girl.

Learn more about Courtney at http://www.Courtney-Ortiz.com! @Ian_IK_Klein Ian “I.K.” Klein is a New York City based dancer and choreographer hailing from Long Island New York. His training includes everything from Classical Ballet, Jazz, Tap, Hip-Hop, Break dancing, Popping, various styles of Ballroom and various Modern techniques. At the age of 17 he was asked to join the faculty of the 2007 Dance Olympus summer tour. He has taught classes throughout the country in various styles of dance demonstrating his passion for the art of movement. Ian believes that the numerous styles of dance should be used like paints on a palette and dips into each of them while creating to ensure that the outcome is covered in hints of Classical Technique to Street edginess with brush strokes of what ever style the choreography calls for. Recently he has performed with artists such as Dita Von Teese, Rita Ora, Conor Maynard, Sean Kingston and Ne-Yo. Ian graduated from Marymount Manhattan College where he majored in dance and received his B.F.A

@DanaAlexaNY Dana Alexa was born in Brooklyn, NY and started her dance training at the tender age of 2 years old. She quickly fell in love with dance and began training seriously at the age of 21. She has trained with the best instructors in the world in hip hop, jazz, street jazz, tap and ballet. She has taught hip hop and street jazz to students of all ages and levels, for HS and college dance teams, studios, pro teams, semi-pro teams and more. Dana began her professional dance career by representing the NBA in NYC as a Knicks City Dancer. She went on to dance with recording artist Kat Deluna on her world promo tour. In addition, Dana became Kat’s choreographer and artistic director and choreographed Kat’s world tour and two music videos. Dana then relocated to Los Angeles to pursue her career on the west coast. Most recently, Dana choreographed and performed on Bravo TV’s Watch What Happens Live and The Real Housewives of NJ. She has worked with artists like Tyga and Wiz Khalifa and has just returned from a tour in China, where she performed, danced in a national commercial, choreographed and taught workshops. Dana was also recently cast as a dancer for a national Lexus commercial. Dana also assists choreographer Matt Steffanina at his weekly LA classes at IDA Hollywood and Millennium Dance Complex. She is featured in countless videos with Matt, some that have reached well over a million views on YouTube and have been posted by celebrities like Will.I.Am, Justin Bieber and Chris Brown. Dana is now represented by The Movement Talent Agency and will continue to pursue her dream with relentless passion and drive.

@Melia_Music Melia Barnes, known in the industry as “Mel B,” started dancing at age nine, training in all styles of dance at the prestigious Larkin Dance Studio in St. Paul, Minnesota. After graduating early from the St. Paul Conservatory of Performing Arts, she relocated to Los Angeles in pursuit of a professional entertainment career. After only a few short months in L.A. she booked her first major gig dancing for Wayne Brady in his headlining show at the Venetian Hotel in Las Vegas. Soon thereafter, she continued her success in the industry dancing for Wade Robson in Cirque Du Soleil’s “Believe” starring Criss Angel. After her contracts were completed, Mel relocated back to Los Angeles and has since continued her career as one of the leading female forces in L.A. dancing for companies and artists such as TLC, Reebok, Redken, America’s Got Talent, Hewlitt-Packard, Macy’s, Keyshia Cole, Capezio, Macy Gray, (and perhaps her favorite job to date) touring world-wide with international superstar Kanye West on his Dark Fantasy Tour. In addition, Mel has choreographed commercially for companies such as Suave Hair and Oscar Meyer; just a few months ago, Mel wrapped filming as head choreographer on both the TLC Network show “Totally T-Boz” starring T-Boz of TLC, and a new pilot starring Wayne Brady. Mel took the stage just a few weeks ago with rap legend Ludacris in Atlanta for the BudLight MusicFirst Tour, and continues to dance with Ludacris currently. Melia has had the opportunity to work alongside such major choreographers as Brian Friedman, Tony Testa, Travis Wall, Rhapsody James, and Tabitha & Napoleon D’Umo. Mel has also had the pleasure of judging for national dance competitions such as StarQuest and Applause. Her unparalleled experience and versatility not only in the highly competitive and technical competition realm, but in the commercial and hip hop dance world of L.A. place her among the top teachers, choreographers, and dance artists in the world. With much pride and excitement, Mel B accepted the position as Director of Showbiz National Talent just this past season, and continues to stay active in all circuits of the dance world. Right now, Melia still resides in L.A. recording her first rap album. She is absolutely ecstatic to be joining the Dance Rogue family for 2014!

@MattSteffanina Matt Steffanina grew in Virginia and began dancing at age 18 when he came across some breakdancing videos. His interest quickly spread to hip hop, and after performing his choreography in a local talent competition he was brought on as the head choreographer of a competitive hip hop dance crew at the University of Virginia. After relocating to Los Angeles in 2010, he quickly began working in the commercial industry dancing for artists such as Chris Brown, Lil Wayne, Jermaine Jackson, Snoop Dogg, DJ Tiesto, Busta Rhymes and Tyga. Matt also performed on shows like So You Think You Can Dance, The Tonight Show with Jay Leno, and choreographed for TV and commercials overseas. Matt has made a big impact online through his YouTube channels and social media. With over 70 MILLION views and over 600,000 subscribers he’s been able to connect with dancers all over the world. In 2012 Matt created Dance Tutorials LIVE, an online dance tutorial library where dancers all over the world can learn how to dance everything from ballet to breakdancing. In it’s first year, Dance Tutorials LIVE got over 10 Million hits and praise from magazines and dance companies nation wide. Matt teaches weekly hip hop classes at Millennium Dance Complex, IDA Hollywood and is also on staff at Movement Lifestyle & Debbie Reynolds. He spends much of the year teaching master classes around the world and also teaches a 3-month “Business For Dancers” course for the IDA Certificate Program.

Katie was born and raised in Wheaton, IL. She began dancing at Moves Dance Studio in North Aurora, IL, at the age of twelve. Two years later, she was invited to audition for Soleunique Dance Company, under the direction of Anthony Foster and Victoria Bunch. She excelled within the company, growing as an artist and technician, and went on to win awards and accolades at a regional and national level. Upon graduating high school, Katie continued her relationship with Soleunique as a company assistant and choreographer. She also began teaching at her home studio, Moves, at this time. While she fell in love with teaching and inspiring others, Katie has made it a point to continue her own dance education. She has attended intensives with Canada’s Royal Winnipeg Ballet and NYC’s Capezio Peridance Center. She was a scholarship student at Visceral Dance Studio and is currently part of the work study program at Lou Conte Dance Studio. Katie also spent three seasons with NoMi Dance Company, formerly NoMi LaMad Dance, Inc. as a company dancer and soloist, where she had the pleasure of training under Laura Kariotis and Madeline Renwick, and dancing works by renowned choreographers such as Nick Pupillo, Autumn Eckman, and Paul Christiano. Katie is currently thriving on freelance work. She has done industrials for UPS and M.A.C. Cosmetics, has danced back-up in the McDonalds Thanksgiving Day Parade for pop artist Sashé Taylor, has performed at Carnival Choreographer’s Ball Chicago, and has been flown into Kansas City to dance behind musical sensation Sunni Stephens. Katie has also modeled on the Steve Harvey Show, live on air with WCUI’s ‘You and Me This Morning’ and has done national print work for dancewear brand MARCEA. Most recently, she was featured on FOX’s ‘Empire’, directed by Lee Daniels. Katie is currently teaching and choreographing all over Chicago-land, specializing in contemporary and jazz, and offers private coaching for technique, and dance team/company audition prep.

PAST SPECIAL GUEST EDUCATORS

@Official_tWitch Stephen “tWitch” Boss had a breakthrough year in 2010, as he starred in the 3rd installment of the Step Up franchise, “Step Up 3D” (Disney, Summit Entertainment). It didn’t stop there, because he also landed a lead role in “Stomp The Yard: Homecoming” (Screen Gems, 2010). If that weren’t enough, he returned to the “So You Think You Can Dance” stage in Season 7, as an All-Star, joined The LXD, in their second season on Hulu.com, and was a guest star on the hit FOX show, ‘Bones’. In 2011, he starred alongside Glee’s Harry Shum Jr. in the critically acclaimed short ‘3 Minutes’ (www.3minutes-film.com ), and signed a 2 picture movie deal with Trimount Pictures. It didn’t stop there, as he reprised his role of ‘Jason’ in Step Up 4. 2012 started with a bang, as he landed a guest star role on the smash hit, ‘Touch’, on FOX. The sky is the limit for tWitch. Boss currently resides in Los Angeles and is on The Board of Directors for The Dizzy Feet Foundation that aims to support, improve, and increase access to dance education for the underprivileged in the United States. He also launched tWitch Boss Clothing in January 2012 that consists of casual street wear. Boss is best known for his amazing performances on the popular Fox dance competition series “So You Think You Can Dance,” where he captivated audiences with his impressive dancing skills and unmatched charisma. Just short of making the Top 20 in Season 3, he came back in Season 4 and was redeemed with a spot on the show and the runner-up title. He was able to work with amazing choreographers like Mia Michaels,= Dave Scott, Tyce DiOrio, and Jean-Marc Genereux—to name a few. In fact, his memorable performance in “Mercy” aka “The Door Dance” alongside Katee Sheen was recently nominated for a 2009 Emmy award for Best Choreography (Mia Michaels). Boss was born and raised in Montgomery, Alabama where as a child he was always seen dancing. At times when he wasn’t allowed to dance, like at school or church, he would resort to “popping and ticking” (a popular hip-hop style of dance) that resembles a twitch to most. That was how he earned the nickname “tWitch.” Learn more about tWitch at http://www.TheOfficialtWitch.com

@Dance9CyrusCyrus “Glitch” Spencer was born in Dallas, Texas but grew up in Atlanta, Georgia. He started dancing at the age of 8, but then took a reprieve to play sports, and then started again at the age of 15. His preferred styles of dancing include Animation, Popping and Robotics. His attention to detail, and love for teaching students proper technique, have made him a fan favorite in the dance education world.

He was the runner up on Season 9 of So You Think You Can Dance. Since then, he has not stopped working in the industry, performing all across the country, shooting commercials and feature films. He will be seen this summer, in the next installment of the smash hit ‘Step Up’ franchise, ‘Step Up: All In.’

@RyanLRamirez Ryan Ramirez first appeared on Season 7 of So You Think You Can Dance, and appeared again Season 8 as a top 12 contestant. Rayn has appeared on other shoes like Glee, The Voice, America’s Got Talent, X-Factor, and the VMA’s dancing with Florance & the Machine. She has also worked with other artist like Beyonce, Black McGrath and R. Kelly.

@DavidMooreTV David Moore has become known in the industry for his fresh and “cool” take on choreography while being a master of storytelling through movement. Originally from Ft. Lauderdale and Orlando, David now resides in Los Angeles. During his time in Florida, his interest in the dance world grew as he gained exposure to concert tours and music videos. It wasn’t long before he was in front of the mirror teaching himself everything he saw on television. Without formal training he was able to learn choreography and movement from anything dance related as he worked toward finding and developing his own style. During his college years, David was chosen to be a contestant on MTV’s Wade Robson Project and went on to become a top 4 finalist. His success on the show inspired him to move to Los Angeles and pursue his career in choreography and dance. Upon arriving in Los Angeles, David began training heavily at the renowned Millennium Dance Studio and was soon given his own class. Since then he has worked for artists such as Jay Sean, Beyonce, Miley Cyrus, Kelly Rowland, Sean Kingston and Busta Ryhmes and in the world of television/commercials on Dancing with the Stars, Pepsi, Adidas, Nike and American Idol. David was brought on by choreographer, Nancy O’Meara for recording artist Carly Rae Jepsen on performances for her #1 single “Call me Maybe.” Most recently, David worked with pop artist Shane Harper (“Good Luck Charlie”) on his video, “Dancing in the Rain” and tour. He is working closely with Midnight Red who are poised to become one of the best American bands to emerge out of the new boy band era and has been tapped to choreograph Jesse McCartney’s upcoming tour. When not working in the States, he has served as a judge and choreographer on Germany’s hit show “VIVA Dancestars” as well as choreographer on “So You Think You Can Dance” (Ukraine). Always intrigued by the creation process, David has also been pursuing his career as a director. He recently directed projects for Victoria Duffield (platinum selling Canadian artist), the Kidzbop World Tour for Disney, Teen Choice Awards for Sean Kingston, The Monsters of Hip Hop Show (Los Angeles), and working in various venues directing alongside the likes of Jamal Sims, Marty Kudelka, Luther Brown, and Tabitha & Napoleon.

@kingofkrump Christopher ‘Lil C’ Toler is best known as being one of the pioneers of krumping, not to mention his choreography and judging on So You Think You Can Dance. In 2005 he appeared as himself in the krumping documentary Rize, and was cast as a featured dancer in the 2007 art exhibit Slow Dancing. Lil C has worked with a variety of musical artists including Missy Elliott, Fall Out Boy, Jennifer Lopez, Ciara, Missy Elliott, Christina Millian, Sean Paul, Fall Out Boy, Gwen Stefani, Se7en, and Madonna.
